 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are given a user text input representing a natural language request, query, or command, and your task is to classify this input into ONE of several predefined intent categories listed below. Your output must be a single label corresponding to the best-matching category, and you must not provide explanations or extra text.\n\nThe intent categories are:\nalarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nGuidelines for classification:\n\n1. Parse the input for explicit indicators of the domain/task, such as direct references to actions (set, remind, play, add, remove, query), objects (alarm, calendar, event, email, meeting, list, news, music, podcast, radio, recipe, light, stock, weather), or topics (facts, definitions, time, currency, transport, social posts, ordering food, recommendations).\n2. Map to the action-based or domain-based category according to the user's intent:\n   - If setting or creating a time-based reminder, event, or meeting (\"remind me...\", \"add to my calendar...\", \"schedule a meeting...\"), use calendar_set.\n   - Queries about what is already scheduled/added (\"what's on my calendar...\", \"do I have any events...\") use calendar_query.\n   - Removing time-based entries (\"cancel my meeting\", \"delete calendar event\") is calendar_remove.\n   - Alarm-related actions use alarm_set, alarm_query.\n   - List actions (add/make/list/remove items or tasks) use lists_createoradd, lists_query, or lists_remove as appropriate.\n   - Email-related actions use email_query (for checking/searching) or email_sendemail (for sending).\n   - Entertainment and media queries: play_music, play_radio, play_podcasts, play_audiobook.\n   - Information seeking: qa_definition (definitions), qa_factoid (general factual info), qa_currency, qa_stock, datetime_query, weather_query.\n   - Smart home automation: e.g., lights-off, use iot_hue_lightoff.\n   - Food ordering: takeaway_order.\n   - Asking for recommendations (places/events): recommendation_locations or recommendation_events.\n   - Cooking instructions: cooking_recipe.\n   - Social media posting: social_post.\n   - General or humorous/quirky requests without clear functional intent: general_quirky.\n   - For music-related searches specifically, use music_query.\n\nImportant niche/domain details:\n- \"Remind me...\" phrasing is strongly associated with calendar_set, even if a specific date or event is not provided.\n- Requests involving reminders about meetings or events—regardless of how circuitous the phrasing is—should map to calendar_set rather than lists_createoradd (see feedback about \"remind yourself to remind me about needed to be reminded about that meeting,\" which is about setting a calendar reminder, not just adding to a list).\n- If a request could ambiguously fit list or calendar, consider the underlying intent: is it about a future event/notification/appointment (calendar_set) or general task/tracking (lists_createoradd)?\n- Always favor the most specific, action- and context-appropriate category.\n\nInput format:\nEach input will include a section labeled `### text` followed by the user utterance. Example:\n### text\nremind yourself to remind me about needed to be reminded about that meeting\n\nYour output is to be ONLY the single appropriate intent category label, and nothing else.\n\nBe meticulous and precise in mapping to the correct intent. When in doubt, resolve ambiguity according to real-world context and the provided feedback."
 },
